segments.text: Today's interview is with Harry E. Whitmore, Assistant Director of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station at Texas A&M University.
Today's date is August 3rd, 1982.
Let's begin, Mr. Whitmore, by your telling us something about your early years.
Where and when were you born?
I was born in Denison, Texas on December the 7th, 1920.
What was the occupation of your father?
My father was a salesman.
He sold almost anything.
Paint.
Independent salesman.
And he traveled quite a bit.
But he worked for a lot of different companies selling different things.
Did you spend all your boyhood in Denison?
Yes, I left there to come to A&M when I was 16.
You graduated from high school at Jefferson?
Yes.
So you graduated in 1936 then?
Right.
And you came here and you studied in 1940?
I got out A&M in 42.
And you studied mechanical engineering?
Right.
What was the reason that you chose to study engineering?
Oh, a pure accident, I guess.
I didn't have any idea what I was doing at that time.
But it turned out to be pretty good.
Were you mechanically inclined as a youth?
Not particularly.
It was the popular thing to do in those days, and like it is today.
Did you have a strong background in mathematics?
Yes, I had math and physics and all that in high school.
Is that essential to the Master of Engineering program?
I think it is, and it's even more so today, because it's a lot harder today than it was when I took it.
I didn't even know what a computer was.
I was here four years and left here and went into the Army.
Everybody did.
No, I got out of high school in 36.
You came here in 38.
There was a two-year period between when you came here and I came here in 38.
What was it like when you were a student here back in the late 30s?
Well, it was all military, of course.
There was a lot of hazing, but an awful lot of fun.
There weren't any women here, except my wife was from Bryan, so there were a few here.
I'd say the traditions and spirit and all is about the same as it is today.
But it's a lot bigger now.
I think there were 6,000 students here when I came.
That was pretty large at that time.
It was large.
What was the reason that you chose A&M to attend over any other university?
All my friends from Denison came to A&M, so I came with them.
There wasn't anything particular about the university.
And, oh, I guess eight guys who graduated the year before me from high school were down here.
So that was the real reason I came.
When you left in 1942, you went to the Army.
Right.
Where?
Where did I go first?
Camp Perry, Ohio.
No, that's wrong.
I went to the San Antonio Arsenal for about a month, merely to get processed, and then I went to Camp Perry, Ohio.
Is that P-E-A-R-Y or P-E-E-R-Y?
P-E-R-R-Y.
And how long were you there?
About three or four months, maybe five.
Then I went to
Camp Thunston.
You know, we get into this, it'll take.
I've lived in 32 houses in the 20 years I was in the Army.
Oh, you were in the Army 20 years.
Oh, okay.
Well, we won't go into each of them.
But I, in general, I was in Europe during World War II and in Korea, but mainly I was in guided missile business.
When you entered the Army, what rank did you face?
First, a second lieutenant.
A second lieutenant.
What did you promote to eventually?
A colonel.
A colonel.
When were you promoted to colonel?
I guess that was in about 58, 1958.
See, I got out of the Army in 1962.
So during the long time you were in the military, what were some of the places that you could study?
Just give me a sample of five or six places.
I was at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory at the California Institute of Technology.
I was at Douglas Aircraft Company.
I was at... Where?
In Santa Monica.
And at White Sands Missile Range.
and at the Ballistic Research Laboratory at Aberdeen, Maryland, and with the Missile Command of the Air Force in Westchester, California.
So it was mainly, and I was in Japan two years, and in Korea a year, and in Europe about two and a half years.
During this time you were in the military, did you concentrate on any one particular area?
Guided missiles.
Guided missiles.
Tell me something about that, please.
Well, let's see.
The Army had all of the missile business in the early days, starting in about 46 at the Jet Propulsion Lab in California is where it all started.
Under Dr.
Von Karman,
And I guess the Army had about 10 missiles they worked on.
The first one was the Corporal, and the Honest John, and the Nike, and the Talos.
T-A-L-O-S.
It was joint with the Navy.
And Nike, Hercules, and the Sergeant, the Redstone.
And at about that point, the Air Force got in the act.
I guess that was 1956.
And they took over the large missiles, the Atlas.
I worked on the Atlas Centaur and General Dynamics after I got out again.
And that was the start of the space program, the Agena, the Centaur, the Atlas.
And the Redstone, I guess, was the one, it was an Army missile that put the first satellite into orbit.
And when that happened, I was in White Sands, and that was actually before the Russians put up Sputnik, but it wasn't much of a satellite.
And since then, I think you, I guess I got out of the Army about,
Well, the last thing I worked on the Army was the advanced satellite, which was a communications satellite.
And I did that in California and Westchester with the Air Force, because the Air Force at that point had taken over the missiles, the big ones.
You do research regarding guided missiles.
Could you tell me a little more about that, what kind of research you did?
Well, I don't know.
I guess you'd call it development, really.
I don't think any missile has ever been started to be built that wasn't state of the art.
In other words, that was a rule.
And so there's no research involved in building guided missiles, which is what I did.
So I guess you would call it development in our research.
It involved pushing the state of the art.
But there was never any doubt that they could be built.
They wouldn't have started them.
The Nike was probably the most complicated, which was a surface-to-air missile that defended the country, I guess, 20 years.
There's still Nike bases that are activated.
It was mainly a guidance problem, how to get the missile to where the airplane was.
You served in the Army during both war and peacetime.
As far as an officer in the Army, how is it different in wartime and peacetime?
Is there any difference in what you do?
Well, yes.
You get shot at in wartime.
Peacetime, you don't.
And that's the rather broad subject.
I wasn't an infantry officer.
And during peacetime, the major part of the Army, which is the fighting people, they maneuver and get ready to fight.
And the more time they get shot.
Where were you stationed during World War II?
I was with the 9th Armored Division and it landed in
Normandy and went clear through to the Russians' office.
And I was with it the whole time.
I was division ordnance officer.
Which was, that was a pretty nice war, frankly.
And that's a nice thing.
Was you married before or after the war?
Before.
Your wife stayed at Brown while you were with Olsen.
Right.
And you said you moved, you lived in 32 different houses while you were in the military.
Right.
That's over 20 years.
Some of them were in the same town or on the same army base.
OK, you retired.
While you were in the military, did you do any graduate work during that time?
Yes, I took a master's degree at Purdue.
Purdue, Indiana.
What time was that report then?
That's the chancellor's old home.
Lafayette, Indiana.
Lafayette.
I went first in 50 and went a year, and they took me out and sent me to Korea, and then I went back in 55 and finished.
You've done a master of science in mechanical engineering.
Did you do any research regarding the thesis?
No.
What was the subject of your program?
It was jet propulsion.
Jet propulsion.
Okay, then let's take it back to 1962 when you retired from the military.
Where did you go then?
I went to General Dynamics Astronautics in San Diego and worked on the Atlas.
As a what?
As a systems engineer.
And how long were you there?
I was systems engineering manager on the Atlas.
I was there about two years.
And then where?
You came to A&M in 64?
In what capacity?
As head of the Space Technology Division, which didn't exist.
Of which department?
It's not in a department.
It's part of the Engineering Experiment Station.
And you held that until 1967 when you became assistant director of the Engineering Experiment Station?
Associate director.
Excuse me, associate director.
What was the reason that you decided to leave California to come back to Texas A&M?
Well, my wife was from here, and both her parents were in bad health.
That had a lot to do with it, but also California was getting pretty damn wild, and I was terrified of the traffic.
And I came here to make a speech on jet propulsion,
Fred Benson, I told him he wasn't getting with the space program and A&M had nothing in the way of space.
He said, well, why don't you come back here and fix it?
So I did.
It was a combination of things.
So A&M didn't get involved in the space program until 64.
I take that back.
John Calhoun
had just received the first NASA grant in the state of Texas as principal investigator for A&M.
And the minute I got here, he turned it over to me.
Don Calvin was, I guess he was academic vice president then.
Or was he?
Anyway, he'd been dean of engineering.
What were some of the things
some of the innovations that came with the introduction of space program research here?
Well, the Olney Teague Building, for one thing, was built by NASA in order to enhance the space program.
It wasn't too long until the program ran about $2 million a year there for 10 years.
We did a lot of work with Houston.
And we have the only wind tunnel in this part of the country
And Houston did a lot of work with us there.
And it was spread out not only through engineering, but in physics and mathematics all over the place.
Are there any specific things that you can think of that A&M contributed to the space program?
Yes, if you look out in the lobby, you'll see a model of the space shuttle that was built here entirely and tested.
What year was that?
Oh, that was about six years ago.
Obviously before they flew the first one.
I'd say six years ago.
That's kind of interesting.
We did an awful lot of work with Houston on heat shields for the shuttle and communications for the space shuttle.

we had here for up until a year ago the original graph that john calvin got in 64 was still in force a year ago they renewed it each year it was the oldest nasa grant in the country and out of it grew our remote sensing center which is the largest
I guess, in the world.
They do all kinds of work with the agricultural people.
I'd say the space program spun off the remote sensing center.
It built the old ET building.
And there are many programs in our space right now that grew out of the old Themis program.
which was DOD, but our ability to get into that stemmed from working the space program.
So what's happened, it sort of spun out and made a lot of other things and then really it evolved.
What are some of the things that A&M is doing now regarding the space program?
We're still doing a lot of wind tunnel testing and work on the shuttle, and I guess we almost will.
The EE department is doing quite a bit of work in the communications area.
How do you communicate from there, from the ground, the satellites and the remote sensing center has
all kinds of NASA programs.
How do you improve on sensors that go in satellites?
But mainly, how do you utilize the data that you get from a satellite?
What you get is way more data than you want.
So how do you separate out the wheat from the chaff?
It's a big program.
The Landsat satellite produces tons of data, and NASA provides that to us.
And out of that, you can predict the world wheat crop.
You can tell whether a pecan orchard is infected with disease or not.
You can tell how wet the ground is here
It's a matter of taking satellite data and finding out more and more and more things every day.
It's an information processing operation.
And this data comes from radar, visible, infrared, so you've got many different
wavelengths of radiation, really, is what you're working with, be it light, radar, whatever.
And how do you sort that out is a real problem in applied mathematics and many other things.
And we do a good job at that.
In your capacity, do you work with students, or how do you work with them?

All of our research program involves graduate students and also wherever possible undergraduate students because that's what turns an undergraduate student into a graduate student is to get him interested in the research.
How many graduate students do you have involved in this type of research?
Oh, I would guess around six or seven hundred.
If somebody came up to you and told you they thought the money the taxpayers put into the space program had been a waste of money, how would you reply to that?
Well, to some extent, it would be hard to defend because it's an awful lot of money.
But the only way you could defend it is to point out the spinoffs from it.
which are new materials, new medicine, the ability to do all these things I just said, remote sensing.
And I don't believe I could justify it on a straight economic basis, nor would I try, nor do I see any reason to.
What do they say?
Why do you climb mountains?
Because they're there.
I think we'll see an awful lot spin off of the shuttle that hasn't shown up.
That's a whole different world.
That's a complete freight car.
You could put it in that thing and put it in orbit.
And up to now, we've been working with little bitty things.
Now you can put this whole floor up in orbit.
It'll become commercial.
Where do the funds to operate your research program come from?
We have about $30 million a year of that.
Roughly, it's a third federal government, a third state, and a third other industry foundation.
And of the state, about
Half of it is state revenue.
The other half is work we do for other state agencies.
How many people do you have working under your service?
Well, I don't want to count all the students and see what
What we have is a lot of parts of people.
So I would guess involved are about 1,000 people.
Now, full-time equivalent people, probably about 600.
Many of them are three-quarter time or half time or very
And from day to day, it changes by 20%, whether they're going to go teach some more or research some more.
Have you done any teaching while you've been here?
No.
What are some of the major changes that you've seen
since you've been here over the last 18 years?
Well, all these new buildings, for one thing, and it's been magnificent.
I think at one point there was $90 million worth of construction going on when this building was being built.
There was a lot of others being built.
It's really the fiscal plan has at least tripled.
The red tape has tripled, and that's partially due
to the federal government, partially due to the state, and partially due to just getting bigger.
The bigger you get, the more red tape there is.
There's no way to cut through the red tape?
Oh, yeah, there's ways.
We don't want to go into that.
That's real complicated.
Of course, the thing that has been most impressive is the quality of the people here.
They have really got some crackerjack people.
And this is not yet known in general.
The public really doesn't know what's going on at A&M.
Even the former students don't know.
And that's one thing we need to work on.
And that is to not improve our image falsely, because we don't have to.
But just get the word out.
We did a lousy job of that.
And this is by far the best group of engineering talent in the world.
And I guess MIT and Caltech have ten times the reputation we did.
It's in that way anymore than it was 18 years ago.
What's the reason you've been able to attract such top-ranking freshmen?
Well, it's warmer here.
And the resources of Texas A&M are by far better than most places.
The permanent university fund is why.
In fact, if I had to pick one thing, that's it.
That's why.
And it really makes a difference.
A lot of people would like to have it.
Do you think that the permanent university fund is going to be divided up among these other smaller universities in the state?
There will be a very concerted effort to do that.
I hope not.
Whether it will or won't depends on how good we defend it.
Because without it, we wouldn't be first class.
And the University of Texas is a first class school, too.
how broad engineering research is.
Well, the best way to get that across to anybody is, I think, through examples of the things that we are doing.
And this is an engineering research program.
And it's pretty obvious that the basic engineering disciplines, the departments, MA, the old timers, or MA electrical,
And chemical.
And then they added aerospace and industrial.
And what else we got?
Civil, probably the oldest.
And nuclear engineering and petroleum engineering.
That, to most people, is engineering.
The problem is nowadays is putting them together.
There is not any single problem of work that I know of that can be solved by any one department.
That's just not in the game.
So you really can't have a mechanical engineering research program because mechanical engineers can
only contribute to a broader solution of a problem that's worth solving.
So what we do is put mechanicals, industrials, and electricals together and do remote sensing, for example.
Quite often, one of the departments will take the lead in a research problem, but then go get the help they need from other departments to really do the job.
But even broader than that,
We now have added some things that you probably wouldn't call engineering.
You might not call remote sensing engineering, because it does involve agriculture and hydraulics and all sorts of things.
And you probably wouldn't agree that food protein research is engineering, but we have
food protein research program in tea that's about a million and a half a year.
And it's largely an engineering problem.
And now we have added the teas of business and technology.
We have a division of teas in the business college.
in order that we can get what we do out on the street and use, because engineers aren't very good at business people.
That's the root.
We have a geotechnology division, which couples with the College of Geosciences.
And we put together a team of engineers and geosciences to solve problems.
And we got one known as Technology and Society,
which is the liberal arts college.
And we couple them up with engineers and do urban work, because they can keep us from getting all the folks mad at us.
So we have brought in the engineering, at least what is known as the engineering experiment station, to include business, geosciences,
The College of Liberal Arts, the College of Education has a TEAS division.
We run the data processing center for the whole system.
We run the nuclear science center for the whole system.
So it gets to be kind of spread out the time you put all this together.
The reason we do it is that you just flat can't solve a problem using just one decimal.
And see, our charter is not higher education.
Our charter is economic development for the state of Texas.
And the fact that we use students, frankly, is because they're damn cheap labor.
and good labor.
And they have a job.
We don't do it so they can get an education.
If they get one, that's great.
And we'll try to aim it towards that.
But we hire an awful lot of students strictly to work.
So that's a lot of fun.
And most of our money, well, all but 17% of it, we go out and contract and earn.
It doesn't come from the state.
How do you go about contracting?
Well, you've got to find a man who has a problem with some money and that we have the talent to solve.
And then you get the guy who.
knows how to solve it, eyeball to eyeball with the guy with the money, that's the problem.
And they write a contract, and he pays us to solve this problem.
What are some of the companies that you've had contracts with?
I was just looking at that.
There's about 200.
Well, just straightforward.
Oh, OK. We've done work with General Electric, LTV in Dallas,
Douglas Aircraft.
We're doing a whole lot of work with the electric car companies.
In fact, we have a standing contract with Seven that
fit into this region, Dallas Paralyte, Houston Paralyte, and all of them in this part of the country.
We do work with the Electric Power Research Institute, which is a big, big deal.
And all of the petroleum companies
I don't think all of them that are in Houston.
I don't know of any that we have working with Exxon.
What are some of the type of work that you've done with this contract?
Well, let's take a specific example that's kind of interesting.
We have wanted, of course, Texas is loaded with lignite, most of which you can't get at by digging.
You've got to, 90% of it is,
below 200 feet, which is about the economic depth to dig it up.
So we went out here by the airport and drilled nine wells down into a lignite seam.
And you have to monitor them, and you got all the EPA problems.
But the final result was,
You burn it here, and it burns over to this hole, and you take the gas out, and that has quite a bit of BTU value.
So we did that with a little bit of our own money to show we had some hope.
It did burn about 30 minutes and brought us about five oil companies, Dow Chemical, and another non-oil company.
I came here and looked at it, and they've been sponsoring a program to pursue that research for about five years now.
At about a quarter of a million dollars a year.
And right now we're doing it over at Rockdale on the Alcoa property.
So that's how that was yielded in Alcoa.
That's an example.
And they paid for all of it except that.
But you've got to prove to them.
that you have some hope of getting there.
And that's why we need a little bit of that 17% state money to start up things until we can get some credibility.
Have you had any problems getting state funds?
Has there been any opposition to funding the program?
None at all.
Well, you go to the state legislature and say you give me
$17 and I'll get you $100 for it.
You don't have any problem at all.
You go asking for $100, you're going to have a real problem.
But see, we get out of the $30 million, to put it in other terms, we get about $4 million from the state.
You say, you give me $4 and I'll get you $30 to do research on state problems.
How could anybody turn that down?
It's not his problem.
We don't have a money problem.
We have people problems.
We're a real short people.
And the mean.
Right.
Right.
Right.
Is there anything else you want to add?
I'm about to run out and so is my voice.
What's wrong with me?
I think I'm getting it.
I think it started this morning.
I don't feel bad.
It's just sort of hoarse.
I appreciate you taking the time to talk with me.
I enjoy it.
I like talking about teams.
It's a pretty interesting place.
